definition: "Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is a liver enzyme involved in the metabolism of glutathione — the body's primary intracellular antioxidant — and in the transfer of amino acids across cell membranes. GGT is found primarily in the liver, kidneys, pancreas, and intestine, but elevated circulating GGT reflects predominantly liver and biliary dysfunction. GGT is more sensitive than ALT or AST for detecting liver stress from alcohol, fatty liver disease, and metabolic dysfunction. Elevated GGT also functions as a marker of systemic oxidative stress, reflecting depletion of the glutathione pathway."
